Astrea of the Stars 09-Aug-21 02:49 PM
Bravo! Bravo, while a somewhat outdated word, is still used as a word of praise and accomplishment. After all, why shouldn't we praise those who've gotten so far? Don't hide away your achievements. On the doors and walls of this place is a symbol of hands clapping. There's also a little 'BRAVO ROOM' label on the door itself. Speaking of which: you can tell there's a lock on the door, but if you're coming in here before the room is fully claimed, it'll allow you in without complain. After the room has been fully claimed, the door will open only if it senses that one of the 4 members of the room are within 5 feet of it from the outside. They don't seem particularly homely - all of the walls and ceilings are made out of a near-black metal, though the lighting in this room is decent enough. There are two sets of bunk beds in each room - enough to hold four people. If you're coming in here for the first time, you can claim any of the beds that hasn't been claimed yet. The beds themselves are incredibly well made - they feel like pure bliss. The mattress feels just right to the touch and immediately adjusts to whoever is laying on it, the covers and blankets feel soft, and the pillows themselves automatically morph into the shape that'll work for you, somehow. Impressive. There are also four cabinets here - they are, oddly enough, wooden, somewhat sticking out from the rest of the place. The cabinets have the name of the person who presumably owns the cabinets, notebook paper and a pencil on top of them, and clothes of whoever owns it. This all is automatically done as the person 'registers' by walking through the door. There's also a trash can to the side of them, emptied out each day. (edited)
Astrea of the Stars 09-Aug-21 10:16 PM
There are two bathrooms to the side. The sink is... a sink, though you notice it has all of the skin, hair, and dental care that you could ever ask for. The toilet is one of the Japanese deluxe toilets that have a variety of features that you have no idea what they do - they can sing to you, clean you up (though there is also toilet paper here), heat your.. bottom, etc. Plenty of towels also line the bathroom, and they seem to be refreshed every day. There's a place to throw your dirty clothes, but of course, there's also the shower, which, while a standing shower, automatically adjusts to the temperature you like and has plenty of hair care and shower products. There's a fancy tub near the shower with much of the same equipment (except there is some special tub equipment, too, so yes, you can have a bubble bath), so that's neat.

Rui Kaida BOT 21-Nov-21 05:49 PM
Rui walked through the remains of the bunker for a long time. There wasn't much to be seen. The creaking of strained metals and the scent of fresh smoke hung in the air, keeping them company for now. The others had been thorough. Some rooms burned, some rooms dismantled, some battered, some broken. Almost none were livable or usable, not for the foreseeable future. Bravo room was untouched. The beds lay empty as they had for weeks, rust coating the frames, contrasted by fresh mattresses and sheets brought by Antomy long ago. Rui gently brushed their hand against their mattress, pulling back sharply as the bed frame shuddered from just the slight touch. They would need to move that. They needed somewhere to sleep. That would have to wait, though. Instead, they sat against the wall, and they stared at the ceiling. It was over. Finally. The revenge Rui spoke of was performed, and freedom was a choice away. For a moment, Rui's observations, their calculations on the capabilities and strengths of the others almost seemed to help. They could read the situation, and during the assault on Drake's mecha, they almost felt a part of the group. They all had the same goal, the same exultation when the robot was brought down. Their calculating, deceptive personality had pulled through. It was something to celebrate. Drake was dead! Finally!
Rui pulled their knees to their chest and made themself small, putting their face in their hands. Yeah. It was over. And the things Rui had done amounted to nothing. The game was won, but the game was lost. There was no place for the person Rui had to be in the outside world. Rui was alone, so Rui could finally sob openly, tears trickling down their arms. They stayed quiet, keeping the silence intact. Rui came from an unfair world. Maybe everyone did, in some way or another. But in their world, the heroes were never the ones to win. Good and evil was a battle lost from the start, because good is composed of the weak, and evil of the strong. What was unclear was the 'how'. Rui always wondered, when they sat alone in their apartment with nothing to do, if being the fair and honest person was what made the heroes weak, and if being unfair made the others strong. There were two reasons their life could've gone wrong, and the ways of 'good' and 'evil' was the easier one to blame. So, in a losing situation, the only choice is to be the 'bad guy'. Be the strong one, shrug off the world and control it how you needed. Others are a means to an end, if you have no other choice. Rui suppressed themself to survive. And they tried hard. Every single time they were overcome with self doubt. The choices they made for no reason but to hurt others. The deaths on their hands. If the world worked as they'd thought, if the villains always won, then they could've left alone, and forget about what they did to survive. Rui Kaida could exist as Rui Kaida again, and the game would have never happened. The thing they had become in pursuit of safety could be left behind.
But reality was cruel, and although Rui could never win as an honest person, the others could. Which trapped Rui as that thing, so long as the others lived and breathed and told. In the corners of their eyes, they saw the corpses watching them. Mistaking shadows and rubble as the faces of Zoe, and Yanna, and Katie, and everyone. Even Drake, but the younger Drake, the one on the disk in the theater. Rui knew it wasn't real, that their mind was broken. They waved without looking up and fell back into their thoughts. Back by the train, Rui knew it was true. Something in them said that the train would really take them somewhere safe and free. But stepping on board, watching the faces of people who despised them, who wished that their place as a survivor was taken by another-- that wasn't something they could bear. They stayed quiet, they stayed small, but they knew. If they spoke, they would be hated as well. And the others would speak of everything, and this time, the entire world would turn against Rui. So they came back, and they cried. They had misunderstood. The rule wasn't about good or evil. It was about Rui, and how they were destined to lose. With bleary eyes and a tear-stained face, Rui looked up into their new home. Rust, ashes, and the phantom scent of blood. Hopefully the farm still worked. The rooms would need to be cleaned, too, before the soot got too deep to get rid of. They turned off their head and resolved to live here, unthinking, until the lights no longer turned on and the food ran dry. Better to be nothing than to be Rui. And as they played the part of nothing, Rui wished it could be real.
